===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|douten||lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|douter||lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|douter||lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|dubitare|lang=la}}. Replaced {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|tweonien||to doubt|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|twēonian}}, compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|twēo||doubt, duplicity}}). The modern spelling is probably under the influence of {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|doubter|lang=frm}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|ambitransitive|lang=en}} To lack confidence in; to [[disbelieve]], [[question]], or [[suspect]].
#: ''He '''doubted''' that was really what you meant.''
#* Hooker
#*: Even in matters divine, concerning some things, we may lawfully '''doubt'''{{...}}
#* Dryden
#*: To try your love and make you '''doubt''' of mine.
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} To [[fear]]; to [[suspect]].
#* '''1819''', Lord Byron, ''Don Juan'', I.186:
#*: He fled, like Joseph, leaving it; but there, / I '''doubt''', all likeness ends between the pair.
# {{cx|obsolete|lang=en}} To fear; to be apprehensive of.
#* R. of Gloucester
#*: Edmond [was a] good man and '''doubted''' God.
#* Shakespeare
#*: I '''doubt''' some foul play.
#* Spenser
#*: I of '''doubted''' danger had no fear.
# {{cx|obsolete|lang=en}} To fill with fear; to [[affright]].
#* Beaumont and Fletcher
#*: The virtues of the valiant Caratach / More '''doubt''' me than all Britain.

